				<div class="info">
					<span class="printuser avatarhover"><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/jacob-conwell" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(1372582); return false;"  ><img class="small" src="http://www.wikidot.com/avatar.php?userid=1372582&amp;amp;size=small&amp;amp;timestamp=1610227428" alt="Jacob Conwell" style="background-image:url(http://www.wikidot.com/userkarma.php?u=1372582)"/></a><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/jacob-conwell" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(1372582); return false;" >Jacob Conwell</a></span> <span class="odate time_1558277875 format_%25e%20%25b%20%25Y%2C%20%25H%3A%25M%7Cagohover">19 May 2019 14:57</span>
														</div>
			</div>
			<div class="content" id="post-content-4254389">
									

<p>Hey Monteparnas, you got a few comments above, so let's take some time to address them.</p>
<div class="collapsible-block">
<div class="collapsible-block-folded"><a class="collapsible-block-link" href="javascript:;">+&nbsp;show&nbsp;block</a></div>
<div class="collapsible-block-unfolded" style="display:none">
<div class="collapsible-block-unfolded-link"><a class="collapsible-block-link" href="javascript:;">–&nbsp;hide&nbsp;block</a></div>
<div class="collapsible-block-content">
<blockquote>
<p>She had some really bad experiences there, and in the end she and the Foundation were kind of trying to re-establish contact.</p>
</blockquote>
<p>Trying does not mean succeeding. It's pretty clear at the end of SCP-2106 that the Foundation had largely broke SCP-2106 beyond meaningful repair. Feel free to give the Foundation an A for effort in attempting to fix the damage they did, but that doesn't make it okay.</p>
<blockquote>
<p>Because at no point was I convinced that she wanted anything resembling that. She didn't seemed to want to die, she didn't seemed to want to go to any particular place. Even the idea that she wanted freedom on a broader sense was implied far more by other people than her.</p>
</blockquote>
<p>Last I checked, the Serpent's Hand were not really in the business of asking prisoners if they wanted to be freed before freeing them. Especially when those prisoners are sapient humanoid anomalies in the custody of the SCPF. Feel free to begrudge the SH for not having that courtesy with respect to SCP-2106's wishes, but their actions here are fully in character for certain characterizations of the GOI.</p>
<blockquote>
<p>Why the WWS liaison did any of this?</p>
</blockquote>
<p>WWS is not in the habit of locking up humanoid anomalies. The SH operative (the crow) simply needed to convince her that SCP-2106 was a person who needed to be freed, and there you go. There doesn't really need to be a whole lot more motivation than that.</p>
<blockquote>
<p>Why the talking crow is doing whatever it is doing?</p>
</blockquote>
<p>Because freeing humanoid anomalies from the SCP Foundation is par for the course for the Serpent's Hand.</p>
<blockquote>
<p>Why it mingles with 3466?</p>
</blockquote>
<p>I don't know about you, but if I was a telepathic crow serving as an SH agent, and wanted to blend in and talk to a WWS worker without drawing a ton of attention, blending in with 3466 would be a pretty good way of going about that.</p>
<blockquote>
<p>More simpler than that, if the Foundation just accepted to deliver 2106 to WWS, why it attacked the convoy at all!? There was no reason, the liaison could give a better life to 2106 at WWS, or free her from there, that would be a lot easier.</p>
</blockquote>
<p>At no point is it ever said that the larger WWS team is on board with Francesca Carpenter's plan. By releasing SCP-2106&#160;en route to WWS, the SH gives them plausible deniability as to their attack. Furthermore, just releasing SCP-2106 at WWS would be incredibly damaging to the WWS/SCPF relationship, since WWS contains anomalies for the Foundation. It doesn't release them, and if it did, its very likely the Foundation would put an end to WWS.</p>
<p>With respect to WWS providing SCP-2106 with a better life, that is arguably true. However, that's just substituting one prison for another in the mind of the Serpent's Hand so it would be rather intolerable to just allow that to happen.</p>
<blockquote>
<p>On a similar note, why the agent didn't pulled the trigger against the bird!? I mean, as tough as the crow talked, it was an easy target right there to do a lot more for the Foundation. Was the crow in control of the attacking party? It seemed at least an important asset to a group that just attacked the Foundation directly.</p>
</blockquote>
<p>Yes. The crow was the leader of this cell of the Serpent's Hand. That was made pretty clear in the tale. As for why Agent Lee didn't pull the trigger on it, well, then he'd have been instantly killed by the surrounding SH agents. SCPF agents aren't mindless goons. They are people. People have self-preservation instincts. As much damage as you could argue would occur in the wake of Agent Lee killing the crow, its fully understandable for him to realize he's outgunned and outmatched, and live to fight another day. Especially when he has downed teammates to look after.</p>
<blockquote>
<p>Sorry, but that story ended up being a complete mess to me. It says nothing except that every character was careless and acted with too little motivation. And even the idea that 2106's condition didn't changed significantly since 2011 seemed off.</p>
</blockquote>
<p>Here is where I really can't help you, I'm afraid.</p>
<p>A lot of your criticisms are pretty easily explained, above, and are based on what appears to be a large misunderstanding of one of the basic tenants of what the Serpent's Hand is and does.</p>
<p>If you don't like the tale, that's fine. Feel free to vote as you will. However, given the above, your reasoning leaves something to be desired.</p>
</div>
</div>
</div>

							</div>

								
					
