		<div class="post" id="post-4254560">
		<div class="long">
			<div class="head">
									<div class="options">
						<a href="javascript:;" onclick="togglePostFold(event,4254560)" class="btn btn-default btn-small btn-sm">Fold</a>
					</div>
								<div class="title" id="post-title-4254560">
																		
															</div>
				<div class="info">
					<span class="printuser avatarhover"><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/monteparnas" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(2926286); return false;"  ><img class="small" src="http://www.wikidot.com/avatar.php?userid=2926286&amp;amp;size=small&amp;amp;timestamp=1610227428" alt="Monteparnas" style="background-image:url(http://www.wikidot.com/userkarma.php?u=2926286)"/></a><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/monteparnas" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(2926286); return false;" >Monteparnas</a></span> <span class="odate time_1558296418 format_%25e%20%25b%20%25Y%2C%20%25H%3A%25M%7Cagohover">19 May 2019 20:06</span>
														</div>
			</div>
			<div class="content" id="post-content-4254560">
									

<p>Thank you for taking the time to answer my comments, this does mean a lot to me. I'll answer what I think that needs to be.</p>
<div class="collapsible-block">
<div class="collapsible-block-folded"><a class="collapsible-block-link" href="javascript:;">+&nbsp;show&nbsp;block</a></div>
<div class="collapsible-block-unfolded" style="display:none">
<div class="collapsible-block-unfolded-link"><a class="collapsible-block-link" href="javascript:;">–&nbsp;hide&nbsp;block</a></div>
<div class="collapsible-block-content">
<p>1- Since she is also trying to establish contact in the end of her article, it is a stretch to presume it was beyond meaningful repair. I'm not against it <strong>being</strong> beyond meaningful repair, but this is an assumption, not a given, and the tale takes this as a given.</p>
<p>Keep in mind that she was able to take it relatively easy on becoming a bunch of crows, so I do expect some mental fortitude from her.</p>
<p>2- I do agree that some sects of the SH could do that, the action was in character for them. But I do question its effect from a story perspective, in that it doesn't give the sensation of closure. And the story doesn't seem focused on showing how heavy-handed the SH can be.</p>
<p>Again, nothing against your portrayal of the Hand, just don't think it contributes to your story.</p>
<p>3- It is on the story to show a character's motivation. At no point I think the motivation of each character isn't believable, I question that it isn't shown at all. On the WWS liaison's case, without going into specifics of the characters and what is going on, she have plenty of reasons to not go in this direction: she doesn't know if this will go fine, she'll actually get to take care of the anomaly if the SH does not interfere, she's spelling big trouble to her entire GOI for the sake of something she doesn't know shit about.</p>
<p>There are plenty of possibilities for those things not be true or not be enough for this particular character, but the story gives none, so I have no investment on this.</p>
<p>4- The crow doesn't need too much of a motivation, because yeah, I can get it pretty much does that because it is a SH terrorist. But then, giving the crows motivation would be a way to give a greater meaning to the story once none can be found elsewhere. The same goes for it mingling with 3466.</p>
<p>5- At no point I considered that the rest of WWS was on board with the plan, but Francesca is a liaison of the WWS, trusted enough to arrange this entire transference. I <strong>do</strong> expect a better judgement from her even if the plan is hers alone. She is WWS, not SH (she could be, but again, this isn't stated in the story), so it is hard to believe she thinks a terrorist attack by a third party is better for 2106 than it being kept at WWS where it will be treated better and probably left to her own devices if she shows they can trust her.</p>
<p>On the trust between groups, yes, if WWS simply lets 2106 escape and the Foundation learns it, there would probably be some really bad blood. But trust is more than that. If 2106 escaped containment it would be a little damaging, but containment breaches are a thing, expected even, so it would just strike as a relatively low level of carelessness. They would probably get it harder to win on containment disputes for quite some time, but eventually get over it.</p>
<p>Terrorist attacks with a lot of lethal victims and a lot of property damage is whole another level to deal with. First of all it is a given to involve a lot of investigation, and those investigations do include the search for inside compromise <strong>by default</strong>. So things will be hard on WWS side first because there will be an investigation, and that is stressful by itself. Then there is the possibility of the Foundation concluding that the WWS had a hand on the attack. And if they do not reach such conclusion, it is still another level of lack of security.</p>
<p>6- Agent Lee is a trained fighter. It doesn't mean not having self-preservation, but it does mean having a lot of other ways to deal with a situation. The first thing you learn when you are trained to deal with criminals that take hostages or intimidate you at gun point is that you shouldn't be confident on their word. From my point of view, Lee had a lot more of a surviving chance against the bunch of deadly terrorists by taking down the head of the group, so it would be easier to intimidate the others into giving up for their own lives.</p>
<p>Lee could also have tried some delaying tactic, keeping the bird talking. That is the preferable course of action for a not-so-bold agent under that situation. Again, conceding is just stupid, because there is no reason whatsoever for the terrorist to live up to their word. The better way of dealing with this is usually to give time for reinforcements to arrive with a better plan of action, they have a greater statistical chance of rescuing you than yourself.</p>
<p>7- Well, actually that's that. I hope my criticism was made clear, since it was questioned (what is fair, no complains here). It is not that I don't understand how the SH works (I do), but they are not the only parties involved and in the end it isn't enough to sell the story to me. The story is perfectly credible (Francesca could be a mole or just be convinced one of several other ways, the SH and the Foundation acted entirely in-character, 2106's opinion wasn't really relevant), but it ended up being meaningless.</p>
</div>
</div>
</div>
<br />
<em>As a courtesy to our readers on mobile devices, please collapse long posts. ~Zyn</em>
<p>It doesn't mean that you hadn't had a meaning for this, and I can be misguided indeed in assuming that it was giving closure to 2106, but ultimately the text do not deliver this meaning as it is now.</p>

							</div>

								
